Salem Chapel NHS in Ontario might be a candidate for the next addition to the national park system. It's in need of help, and should get it, plus a proper visitor center to interpret its history and association with Harriet Tubman. It might then join with two other Tubman sites in the US to form an International Historical Park. That would raise its profile to a level deserving of such a site. https://www.thestar.com/news/gta/2017/12/29/church-attended-by-harriet-tubman-in-need-of-repairs-trustee-says.html Harriet Tubman Underground Railroad National Historical Park Harriet Tubman Home, Authentic and Historic [[PHOTO]]

Point Pelee National Park will be featured on a postage stamp that comes out January 15, as part of a set of nine scenic places across the country. It's a nod to the park's centennial in 2018. Thanks to Woodside staff for baking batches, and preparing a mulled apple cider on an antique stove to accompany the treat.
December 17 marked King's birthday. Did the site do anything special? 

Woodside closed for the season on December 23, and will not reopen until NEXT OCTOBER. It is shameful for a national park system unit to be closed so much of the year, denying visitors the opportunity of seeing this treasure.

Woodside also lacks a visitor center to interpret the life and accomplishments of history's longest-serving prime minister. Its newest addition is an impressive picnic shelter/prep kitchen on the site of a historic coach house, long since gone. But a visitor centre is what's needed, including a gift shop. The current 'shop' is an anemic shelf display of a half dozen items, most of them not related to King or Woodside. It's embarrassing. Woodside National Historic Site [[PHOTO]]

Being a total fan girl of the Canadian parks, I have written before about my solo venture around the Canadian Rockies' Parks. One of my most memorable moments of 2017 is pictured here. I had arrived in Banff, and had to wait for a parking spot at busy Moraine Lake. I started chatting with a bus driver and mentioned that I couldn't believe the people on the Rock Pile. He told me to go do it. I am terrified of heights and knew that would be far outside my comfort zone. He told me several more times that I needed to do it. I walked around the lake for a bit and couldn't shake the feeling that I sort of wanted to try. Clearly, you can see that I did make it up on my jello legs. I shook the whole time and was embarrassingly encouraged by fellow walkers, but it was worth it! Just stunning! When I came down, a beautiful butterfly landed on my shoulder. I am so thankful to that bus driver. I wish he had been there to thank in person when I was done. What a view it was! I cannot wait to go back! [[PHOTO]]
What an inspiring story behind this beautiful photo! Thank you for sharing your experience with us, Jen, and congrats on completing the #ParksChallenge 🎉

It was a "dream-come-true" road trip to a couple of the Parks Canada sites this past summer. Ever since the Centennial year... I've dreamt of going to the East Coast... It took me 50 years... but my husband and I drove from Ontario to most of the Maritime provinces in 7 days. Although Peggy's Cove was my one spot I had to experience... ( more than I expected 🙂)... Anne of Green Gables and Cabot Trail were the two official Parks Canada sites we visited. They didn't disappoint either! We did travel to see other beautiful sites as well... it's a trip that should be on everyone's "Bucket List" to do, at least once! We have such a beautiful Country... and should be experienced in person ... "Oh Canada, our Home and Native Land!" 🇨🇦️ [[PHOTO]]

That sounds like an amazing trip, Cathy! We're so happy you were able to travel to the East Coast and visit our beautiful sites! Thanks for sharing your photo and congrats on completing the #ParksChallenge 🎉

The West Coastal Trail at Fundy Park, the best and worse moment. A group hike gone wrong sadly. It taught me that I was capable to continue a journey even in the hardest of situations. I made it to the end of the trail, had a meltdown and found resolve even in the biggest upset. I still have no idea how I didn’t get hypothermia in the cold Fundy fog (had no idea fog could get that cold) in the middle of August. I’m still a rookie trail adventurer but learned lots. [[PHOTO]]
Wow, that's an impressive story! Thank you for sharing your experience with us - and this great selfie! Congrats on completing the #ParksChallenge 🎉

This past summer, I took my two kids out on a 4 week camping/road trip through BC and Alberta, hitting 5 National Parks Canada along the way.  I've been thinking all morning of this momentous trip, trying to pick one photo, one park, one experience, that defined our journey through these provinces, and was unable to choose.  While each of the parks was stunning in its own display of lakes and rivers, peaks and valleys, animals and birds, plants and trees, I was most impressed by the staff who worked all hours, the interpreters who taught all ages, the rangers who protected all areas, the firefighters who managed all fires, and the road crews who directed all travelers in and around the parks.  We had a most glorious time learning more about this amazing country we call home, and I would like to commend Parks Canada for all the work it does to preserve the local environments and stories of this land.  We can't wait to return in 2018.

(Mount Revelstoke and Glacier national parks Yoho National Park, Jasper National Park, Banff National Park)🌲🌳🍃 [[PHOTO]]

A senior porcupine who spent the end of fall under our deck, eating on our lawn.  Unfortunately it passed away about a week ago.  I'm assuming due to a cold spell we had and the fact that it wasn't denning properly.  We had at least 5 living on the edge of our property all summer.  Our husky doesn't react to them so the shepherd learned from her not to as well.  The husky can be left outside alone with it, although she does get worried when it wanders to close to her!  They dogs became so used to it being there when we went out that one was very upset over it's death (she was also the one who found it). [[PHOTO]]
We're sorry to hear that! Thank you for sharing this lovely photo and the story behind it. Best wishes to you and your dogs <3

When identifying pictures taken in Kluane, it would be good to know whether they are in the national park or in the area set aside to *become* national parkland (the Reserve). The two areas are separate. There is no one unit called "Kluane National Park and Reserve". It's either Kluane NP or Kluane NP Reserve. Unless photos are taken near the boundary of the two, one picture can't include both.

Someone at National Park Service (Fan Page) asked which park units folks had visited in 2017. This was my result. The original post, there, contains links to all park Facebook pages (see Jan. 2):

When Neil Lynch asked which park units folks visited in 2017, it got me counting, for I knew it was a big year, personally. Thank you, Neil. I never would have totaled them, otherwise. The result: 49 park system units last year. The 150th year of Confederation, combined with free admission to Parks Canada sites, led me to visit and re-visit several in Ontario and Quebec, plus the USA. The tally and list:

Ontario: 16
Quebec: 20
USA:   13
Total: 49 national park units

This list does not include visits to dozens of NHS's which are *not* in the park system. Feel free to ask any questions about these places.

Ontario:

Thousand Islands National Park (x 2)
Rouge National Urban Park
Woodside National Historic Site
HMCS Haida National Historic Site
Queenston Heights NHS
Fort George National Historic Site
Battlefield of Fort George NHS
Butler's Barracks NHS
Trent-Severn Waterway NHS (x 3)
Bellevue House National Historic Site
Rideau Canal NHS (x 4)
Laurier House NHS
Glengarry Cairn NHS
Inverarden House NHS
Battle of the Windmill NHS (x 2)
Fort Wellington NHS (x 2)

Quebec:

La Mauricie National Park
Saguenay-St. Lawrence National Marine Park (x 6)
Manoir Papineau NHS
The Fur Trade at Lachine NHS (x 3)
Lachine Canal NHS (x 5)
Sir George-Étienne Cartier NHS
Louis-Joseph Papineau NHS
Saint Maurice Ironworks NHS (x 2)
Cartier-Brébeuf NHS (x 2)
Fortifications of Québec NHS (x 7)
Quebec Garrison Club NHS
57-63 St. Louis Street NHS (x 3)
Maillou House NHS (x 4)
Montmorency Park NHS (x 5)
Saint-Louis Forts and Châteaux NHS (x 9)
Lévis Forts NHS
Grosse Île and the Irish Memorial NHS
Battle of the Chateauguay NHS
Coteau-du-Lac NHS

National park system units in the USA:

Gauley River National Recreation Area
New River Gorge National River
Blue Ridge Parkway
Guilford Courthouse National Military Park
Kings Mountain National Military Park
Cowpens National Battlefield
Carl Sandburg Home National Historic Site
Andrew Johnson National Historic Site
Cumberland Gap National Historical Park (x 2)
William Howard Taft National Historic Site
Charles Young Buffalo Soldiers National Monument
Dayton Aviation Heritage National Historical Park
Fallen Timbers Battlefield & Fort Miamis NHS (affiliated)
